# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grub-bootloader
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:grub-bootloader/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] A **bootloader**, also spelled as **boot loader** or called **bootstrap loader**, is a computer program that is responsible for booting a computer and booting an operating system.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] If it also provides an interactive menu with multiple boot choices then it is often called a **boot manager**.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Examples of first-stage bootloaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot, and Das U-Boot.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] It initializes hardware devices such as CPU, motherboard, memory, storage and other I/O devices.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Second-stage boot loaders, such as GNU GRUB, rEFInd, BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and NTLDR, are not themselves operating systems, but are able to load an operating system properly and transfer execution to it; the operating system subsequently initializes itself and may load extra device drivers.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Second-stage implementations can include interactive user interfaces, allowing boot option selection and parameter modification.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] They handle kernel loading, including processing of initrd/initramfs images, and can pass boot parameters to the kernel.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Many implement modular designs supporting loadable modules for additional functionality.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] They may also handle compression, cryptographic verification, and chain-loading of other bootloaders.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] In x86 computers, after the BIOS executes Power-On Self Test, it executes the first-stage bootloader, which is a compact 512-byte program that resides in the master boot record (MBR).
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Running in 16-bit real mode at address 0x7C00, it locates the second-stage bootloader.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Its primary challenge lies in accomplishing these tasks within strict size constraints while handling potential hardware failures.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] The bootloader must navigate disk structures, often implementing FAT file system support, and manage the delicate transition from the BIOS startup state to a stable environment for the next boot stage.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] Microsoft boot sectors, therefore, traditionally imposed certain restrictions on the boot process.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] For example, the boot file had to be located at a fixed position in the root directory of the file system and stored within consecutive sectors, conditions taken care of by the `SYS` command and slightly relaxed in later versions of DOS.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] When Microsoft added logical block addressing (LBA) and FAT32 support, they switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors, using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KiB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file systems, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] In x86 computers, second-stage bootloaders, such as PBR, operate without the strict 512-byte limitation of their first-stage counterparts.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] They execute in a more sophisticated environment, typically ranging from 8KB to several megabytes in size.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] This expanded space allows implementation of complex features such as filesystem support, runtime configuration, and bootloader menu interfaces.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] In x86 computers, third-stage bootloaders include IO.SYS, NTLDR, BOOTMGR, and GRUB.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] UEFI (except for CSM boot) does not rely on boot sectors; it directly loads the next-stage bootloader (such as BOOTMGR and GRUB2) from the EFI System Partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] At the completion of the operation, the system stores the I/O address in the halfword at location 2 and loads the PSW from location 0.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] The operating systems for S/360 through z/Architecture reside on direct access storage devices (DASDs), e.g., disk, drum.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] For these devices, *Read IPL* does a seek to cylinder 000016, head 000016, and orients to record 0116.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] For all supported operating systems, record 0116 contains a *Read Data* CCW to read a *bootstrap record* and a *Transfer In Channel* (TIC) CCW to the bootstrap.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] The channel program in the bootstrap reads the IPL program text into location 0, beginning with a PSW pointing to the first IPL program text instruction.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] For OS/360 the IPL program does some initialization, relocates itself, locates the *Nucleus*, loads the nucleus and transfers to the *Nucleus Initialization Program* (NIP) at the end of the Nucleus.
[src:grub-bootloader/bootloader] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over the control of the booting process.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GNU GRUB was developed from a package called the *Grand Unified Bootloader* (a play on Grand Unified Theory).
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] It is predominantly used for Unix-like systems.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] When an IBM PC compatible computer with a BIOS is turned on, the BIOS finds the primary bootable device (usually the computer's hard disk) and runs the initial bootstrap program from the master boot record (MBR).
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The MBR is the first sector of the hard disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] This bootstrap program must be small because it has to fit in a single sector.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] For a long time, the size of a sector has been 512 bytes.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Since 2009 there are hard disks available with a sector size of 4096 bytes, called Advanced Format disks, but as of October 2013, such hard disks are still accessed in 512-byte sectors, using the 512e emulation.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The legacy MBR partition table supports a maximum of four partitions and occupies 64 bytes, combined.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Together with the optional disk signature (four bytes) and disk timestamp (six bytes), this leaves between 434 and 446 bytes available for the machine code of a boot loader.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Although such a small space can be sufficient for very simple boot loaders, it is not big enough to contain a boot loader supporting complex and multiple file systems, menu-driven selection of boot choices, etc.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Boot loaders with bigger footprints are therefore split into pieces, where the smallest piece fits in the MBR, while one or more larger pieces are stored in other locations such as empty sectors between the MBR and the first partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The code in the MBR then does little more than starting the second part.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The purpose of the remaining part(s) of the boot loader is to actually boot an operating system by configuring it and starting the kernel.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Kernels are in most cases stored as files residing on appropriate file systems, but the concept of a file system is unknown to the BIOS.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Thus, in BIOS-based systems, the duty of a boot loader is to access the content of those files, so it can be loaded into the RAM and executed.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] One possible approach for boot loaders is to load kernel images by directly accessing hard disk sectors without understanding the underlying file system.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Usually, an additional level of indirection is required, in form of *maps* or *map files* – auxiliary files that contain a list of physical sectors occupied by kernel images.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Such maps need to be updated each time a kernel image changes its physical location on disk, due to installing new kernel images, file system defragmentation, etc.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Also, in case of the maps changing their physical location, their locations need to be updated within the boot loader's MBR code, so the sectors indirection mechanism continues to work.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] This is not only cumbersome, but it also leaves the system in need of manual repairs in case something goes wrong during system updates.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Another approach is to make a boot loader aware of the underlying file systems, so kernel images are configured and accessed using their actual file paths.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] That requires a boot loader to contain a driver for each of the supported file systems, so they can be understood and accessed by the boot loader itself.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] This approach eliminates the need for hardcoded locations of hard disk sectors and existence of map files, and does not require MBR updates after kernel images are added or moved around.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The configuration of a boot loader is stored in a regular file, which is also accessed in a file system-aware way to obtain boot configurations before the actual booting of any kernel images.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Thus, fewer things can go wrong during system updates.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] As a downside, such boot loaders are larger and more complex.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GNU GRUB uses the second approach, by understanding the underlying file systems.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The boot loader itself is split into multiple *stages* so that it fits in the MBR boot scheme.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Two major versions of GRUB are in common use: GRUB version 0, called *GRUB legacy,* is only prevalent in older releases of Linux distributions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] *GRUB 2* was written from scratch and intended to replace its predecessor, and is now used by a majority of Linux distributions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The master boot record (MBR) usually contains GRUB *stage 1,* or can contain a standard MBR implementation which chainloads GRUB *stage 1* from the active partition's boot sector.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Given the small size of a boot sector (512 bytes), *stage 1* can do little more than load the next stage of GRUB by loading a few disk sectors from a fixed location near the start of the disk (within its first 1024 cylinders).
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GRUB presents a menu where the user can choose from operating systems (OS) found by grub-install.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GRUB can be configured to automatically load a specified OS after a user-defined timeout.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] If the timeout is set to zero seconds, pressing and holding ⇧ Shift, or in some modern GRUB versions loaded using UEFI, pressing Esc rapidly while the computer is booting makes it possible to access the boot menu.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Once boot options have been selected, GRUB loads the selected kernel into memory and passes control to the kernel.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Alternatively, GRUB can pass control of the boot process to another boot loader, using *chain loading*.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] This is the method used to load operating systems that do not support the Multiboot Specification or are not supported directly by GRUB.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] A computer can have multiple hard disks connected to it.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] These could be identified via their SATA port.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Each time the computer POSTs, the hard disk connected to a specific motherboard port *could* be assigned the same identifier, for example `hd0, hd1, …`.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] But what if such consistency cannot be guaranteed?
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] What if the constellation of connected hard disks changed from one start up to another?
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] What if a hard disk will be connected to another computer?
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] By entering `ls` into either the *GRUB rescue console* (available after loading `core.img` ) or the *GRUB console* (available after loading `normal.mod`) a list of all available hard disks and partitions can be obtained.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] For example, `ls (hd0,5)/`) will show numbers that can be assigned to actual hard disks and partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] As it cannot be guaranteed that the "`hd0"`style numbering of hard disks via device numbers is consistent, GNU GRUB can use a Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) to identify partitions (actually file system instances).
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The file systems ext2, ext3, ext4 and xfs use a UUID to uniquely identify an instance.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The UUID is created when a partition is formatted.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The UUID is part of the file system and written to the superblock.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] All operations other than formatting should leave the UUID unaltered.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] It is possible to change the UUID or duplicate it by using dd to clone an entire partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The file `grub.cfg` is used to configure GRUB.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] It contains commands to be executed during each start-up.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Without an existing and valid `grub.cfg`, GRUB will present a prompt.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] A fancier `grub.cfg` will describe a menu to be presented, use multiple colors, and may specify a background picture.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GRUB was initially developed by Erich Boleyn as part of work on booting the operating system GNU/Hurd, developed by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] In 1999, Gordon Matzigkeit and Yoshinori K.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Okuji made GRUB an official software package of the GNU Project and opened the development process to the public.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] By 2014, the majority of Linux distributions have adopted GNU GRUB 2.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GRUB version 0 (also known as "GRUB Legacy") is no longer under development and is being phased out.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The GNU GRUB developers have switched their focus to GRUB 2, a complete rewrite with goals including making GNU GRUB cleaner, more robust, more portable and more powerful.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] PUPA was supported by the Information-technology Promotion Agency (IPA) in Japan.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] PUPA was integrated into GRUB 2 development around 2002, when GRUB version 0.9x was renamed GRUB Legacy.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GNU GRUB version 2.00 was officially released on June 26, 2012.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Three of the most widely used Linux distributions use GRUB 2 as their mainstream boot loader.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Ubuntu adopted it as the default boot loader in its 9.10 version of October 2009.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Fedora followed suit with Fedora 16 released in November 2011.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] OpenSUSE adopted GRUB 2 as the default boot loader with its 12.2 release of September 2012.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Solaris also adopted GRUB 2 on the x86 platform in the Solaris 11.1 release.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Buildroot also uses GNU GRUB for x86 and x86_64 targets.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] In late 2015, the exploit of pressing backspace 28 times to bypass the login password was found and quickly fixed.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] In March 2026, the development moved to freedesktop.org.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GNU GRUB is free software, so several variants have been created.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The setup tools in use by various distributions often include modules to set up GRUB.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] For example, YaST2 on SUSE Linux and openSUSE distributions and Anaconda on Fedora/RHEL distributions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] StartUp-Manager and GRUB Customizer are graphical configuration editors for Debian-based distributions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The development of StartUp-Manager stopped on May 6, 2011, after the lead developer cited personal reasons for not actively developing the program.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GRUB Customizer is also available for Arch-based distributions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] For GRUB 2 there are KDE Control Modules.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] GRLDR ICE is a tiny tool for modifying the default configuration of grldr file for GRUB4DOS.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Boot-Repair is a simple graphical tool for recovering from frequent boot-related problems with GRUB and Microsoft Windows bootloader.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] This application is available under GNU GPL license.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Boot-Repair can repair GRUB on multiple Linux distributions including, but not limited to, Debian, Ubuntu, Mint, Fedora, openSUSE, and Arch Linux.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Grub2Win is a Windows open-source software package.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] It allows GNU GRUB to boot from a Windows directory.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The setup program installs GNU GRUB version 2.12 to an NTFS partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] A Windows GUI application is then used to customize the GRUB boot menu, themes, UEFI boot order, scripts etc.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] All GNU GRUB scripts and commands are supported for both UEFI and legacy systems.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] Grub2Win can configure GRUB for multiboot of Windows, Ubuntu, openSUSE, Fedora and many other Linux distributions.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] It is freely available under GNU GPL License at SourceForge.
[src:grub-bootloader/gnu-grub] The strength of GRUB is the wide range of supported platforms, file systems, and operating systems, making it the default choice for distributions and embedded systems.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The **GUID Partition Table** (**GPT**) is a standard for the layout of partition tables of a physical computer storage device, such as a hard disk drive or solid-state drive.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] It is part of the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) standard.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] It has several advantages over master boot record (MBR) partition tables, such as support for more than four primary partitions and 64-bit rather than 32-bit logical block addresses (LBA) for blocks on a storage device.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The larger LBA size supports larger disks.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Some BIOSes support GPT partition tables as well as MBR partition tables, in order to support larger disks than MBR partition tables can support.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] GPT uses universally unique identifiers (UUIDs), which are also known as globally unique identifiers (GUIDs), to identify partitions and partition types.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] All modern personal computer operating systems support GPT.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Some, including macOS and Microsoft Windows on the x86 architecture, support booting from GPT partitions only on systems with EFI firmware, but FreeBSD and most Linux distributions can boot from GPT partitions on systems with either the BIOS or the EFI firmware interface.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The Master Boot Record (MBR) partitioning scheme, widely used since the early 1980s, had limitations when it came to modern hardware.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The available size for block addresses and related information is limited to 32 bits.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] For hard disks with 512‑byte sectors, the MBR partition table entries allow a maximum size of 2 TiB (232 × 512‑bytes) or 2.20 TB (2.20 × 1012 bytes).
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] In the late 1990s, Intel developed a new partition table format as part of what eventually became the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI).
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The GUID Partition Table is specified in chapter 5 of the UEFI 2.11 specification.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] GPT uses 64 bits for logical block addresses, allowing a maximum disk size of 264 sectors.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] In 2010, hard-disk manufacturers introduced drives with 4,096‑byte sectors (Advanced Format).
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] For compatibility with legacy hardware and software, those drives include an emulation technology (512e) that presents 512‑byte sectors to the entity accessing the hard drive, despite their underlying 4,096‑byte physical sectors.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Performance could be degraded on write operations, when the drive is forced to perform two read-modify-write operations to satisfy a single misaligned 4,096‑byte write operation.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Since April 2014, enterprise-class drives without emulation technology (4K native) have been available on the market.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Readiness of the support for 4 KB logical sectors within operating systems differs among their types, vendors and versions.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] For example, Microsoft Windows supports 4K native drives since Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 (both released in 2012) in UEFI.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Like MBR, GPT uses logical block addressing (LBA) in place of the historical cylinder-head-sector (CHS) addressing.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The protective MBR is stored at LBA 0, and the GPT header is in LBA 1.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The GPT header has a pointer to the partition table (*Partition Entry Array*), which is typically at LBA 2.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Each entry in the partition table has the same size, which is 128 or 256 or 512, etc., bytes; typically this size is 128 bytes.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The UEFI specification stipulates that a minimum of 16,384 bytes, regardless of sector size, are allocated for the Partition Entry Array.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Thus, on a disk with 512-byte sectors, at least 32 sectors are used for the Partition Entry Array, and the first usable block is at LBA 34 or higher, while on a 4,096-byte sector disk, at least 4 sectors are used for the Partition Entry Array, and the first usable block is at LBA 6 or higher.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] In addition to the primary GPT header and Partition Entry Array, stored at the beginning of the disk, there is a backup GPT header and Partition Entry Array, stored at the end of the disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The backup GPT header must be at the last block on the disk (LBA -1) and the backup Partition Entry Array is placed between the end of the last partition and the last block.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] For limited backward compatibility, the space of the legacy Master Boot Record (MBR) is still reserved in the GPT specification, but it is now used in a way that prevents MBR-based disk utilities from misrecognizing and possibly overwriting GPT disks.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] This is referred to as a *protective MBR*.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] A single partition of type EEh, encompassing the entire GPT drive (where "entire" actually means as much of the drive as can be represented in an MBR), is indicated and identifies it as GPT.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Operating systems and tools which cannot read GPT disks will generally recognize the disk as containing one partition of unknown type and no empty space, and will typically refuse to modify the disk unless the user explicitly requests and confirms the deletion of this partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Furthermore, GPT-aware OSes may check the protective MBR and if the enclosed partition type is not of type EEh or if there are multiple partitions defined on the target device, the OS may refuse to manipulate the partition table.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] If the actual size of the disk exceeds the maximum partition size representable using the legacy 32-bit LBA entries in the MBR partition table, the recorded size of this partition is clipped at the maximum, thereby ignoring the rest of the disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] This amounts to a maximum reported size of 2 TiB, assuming a disk with 512 bytes per sector (see 512e).
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] It would result in 16 TiB with 4 KiB sectors (4Kn), but since many older operating systems and tools are hard coded for a sector size of 512 bytes or are limited to 32-bit calculations, exceeding the 2 TiB limit could cause compatibility problems.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] In operating systems that support GPT-based boot through BIOS services rather than EFI, the first sector may also still be used to store the first stage of the bootloader code, but modified to recognize GPT partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The bootloader in the MBR must not assume a sector size of 512 bytes.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The partition table header defines the usable blocks on the disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] It also defines the number and size of the partition entries that make up the partition table (offsets 80 and 84 in the table).
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] After the primary header and before the backup header, the Partition Entry Array describes partitions, using a minimum size of 128 bytes for each entry block.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The starting location of the array on disk, and the size of each entry, are given in the GPT header.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The first 16 bytes of each entry designate the partition type's globally unique identifier (GUID).
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] For example, the GUID for an EFI system partition is C12A7328-F81F-11D2-BA4B-00A0C93EC93B.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] The second 16 bytes are a GUID unique to the partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Then follow the starting and ending 64 bit LBAs, partition attributes, and the 36 character (max.) Unicode partition name.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] As is the nature and purpose of GUIDs and as per RFC 4122, no central registry is needed to ensure the uniqueness of the GUID partition type designators.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Windows 7 and earlier do not support UEFI on 32-bit platforms, and therefore do not allow booting from GPT partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] "Partition type GUID" means that each partition type is strictly identified by a GUID number unique to that type, and therefore partitions of the same type will all have the same "partition type GUID".
[src:grub-bootloader/guid-partition-table] Each partition also has a "partition unique GUID" as a separate entry, which as the name implies is a unique id for each partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] A **master boot record** (**MBR**) is a type of boot sector in the first block of partitioned computer mass storage devices like fixed disks or removable drives intended for use with IBM PC-compatible systems and beyond.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The concept of MBRs was publicly introduced in 1983 with PC DOS 2.0.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR holds the information on how the disc's sectors (A.K.A.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] "blocks") are divided into partitions, each partition notionally containing a file system.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR also contains executable code to function as a loader for the installed operating system—usually by passing control over to the loader's second stage, or in conjunction with each partition's volume boot record (VBR).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This MBR code is usually referred to as a boot loader.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The organization of the partition table in the MBR limits the maximum addressable storage space of a partitioned disk to 2 TiB (232 × 512 bytes).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Therefore, the MBR-based partitioning scheme has been superseded by the GUID Partition Table (GPT) scheme in almost all new computers.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] A GPT can coexist with an MBR in order to provide some limited form of backward compatibility for older systems.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] MBRs are not present on non-partitioned media such as floppies, superfloppies or other storage devices configured to behave as such, nor are they necessarily present on drives used in non-PC platforms.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Support for partitioned media, and thereby the master boot record (MBR), was introduced with IBM PC DOS 2.0 in March 1983 in order to support the 10 MB hard disk of the then-new IBM Personal Computer XT, still using the FAT12 file system.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The original version of the MBR was written by David Litton of IBM in June 1982.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The partition table supported up to four *primary partitions*.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This did not change when FAT16 was introduced as a new file system with DOS 3.0.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Support for an *extended partition*, a special primary partition type used as a container to hold other partitions, was added with DOS 3.2, and nested *logical drives* inside an extended partition came with DOS 3.30.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Since MS-DOS, PC DOS, OS/2 and Windows were never enabled to boot off them, the MBR format and boot code remained almost unchanged in functionality (except some third-party implementations) throughout the eras of DOS and OS/2 up to 1996.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In 1996, support for logical block addressing (LBA) was introduced in Windows 95B and MS-DOS 7.10 (Not to be confused with IBM PC-DOS 7.1) in order to support disks larger than 8 GB.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This also reflected the idea that the MBR is meant to be operating system and file system independent.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] However, this design rule was partially compromised in more recent Microsoft implementations of the MBR, which enforce CHS access for FAT16B and FAT32 partition types 0x06/0x0B, whereas LBA is used for 0x0E/0x0C.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Despite sometimes poor documentation of certain intrinsic details of the MBR format (which occasionally caused compatibility problems), it has been widely adopted as a de facto industry standard, due to the broad popularity of PC-compatible computers and its semi-static nature over decades.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This was even to the extent of being supported by computer operating systems for other platforms.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Sometimes this was in addition to other pre-existing or cross-platform standards for bootstrapping and partitioning.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] MBR partition entries and the MBR boot code used in commercial operating systems, however, are limited to 32 bits.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Therefore, the maximum disk size supported on disks using 512-byte sectors (whether real or emulated) by the MBR partitioning scheme (without 32-bit arithmetic) is limited to 2 TiB.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Consequently, a different partitioning scheme must be used for larger disks, as they have become widely available since 2010.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR partitioning scheme is therefore in the process of being superseded by the GUID Partition Table (GPT).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The official approach does little more than ensuring data integrity by employing a *protective MBR*.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Specifically, it does not provide backward compatibility with operating systems that do not support the GPT scheme as well.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Meanwhile, multiple forms of *hybrid MBRs* have been designed and implemented by third parties in order to maintain partitions located in the first physical 2 TiB of a disk in both partitioning schemes "in parallel" and/or to allow older operating systems to boot off GPT partitions as well.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The present non-standard nature of these solutions causes various compatibility problems in certain scenarios.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR consists of 512 or more bytes located in the first sector of the drive.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] IBM PC DOS 2.0 introduced the `FDISK` utility to set up and maintain MBR partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] When a storage device has been partitioned according to this scheme, its MBR contains a partition table describing the locations, sizes, and other attributes of linear regions referred to as partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The partitions themselves may also contain data to describe more complex partitioning schemes, such as extended boot records (EBRs), BSD disklabels, or Logical Disk Manager metadata partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR is not located in a partition; it is located at a first sector of the device (physical offset 0), preceding the first partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] An artifact of hard disk technology from the era of the PC XT, the partition table subdivides a storage medium using units of cylinders, heads, and sectors (CHS addressing).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] These values no longer correspond to their namesakes in modern disk drives, as well as being irrelevant in other devices such as solid-state drives, which do not physically have cylinders or heads.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In the CHS scheme, sector indices have (almost) always begun with sector 1 rather than sector 0 by convention, and due to an error in all versions of MS-DOS/PC DOS up to including 7.10, the number of heads is generally limited to 255 instead of 256.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] When a CHS address is too large to fit into these fields, the tuple (1023, 254, 63) is typically used today, although on older systems, and with older disk tools, the cylinder value often wrapped around modulo the CHS barrier near 8 GB, causing ambiguity and risks of data corruption.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Due to the limits of CHS addressing, a transition was made to using LBA, or logical block addressing.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Both the partition length and partition start address are sector values stored in the partition table entries as 32-bit quantities.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The sector size used to be considered fixed at 512 (29) bytes, and a broad range of important components including chipsets, boot sectors, operating systems, database engines, partitioning tools, backup and file system utilities and other software had this value hard-coded.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Alleviating this capacity limitation was one of the prime motivations for the development of the GPT.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] However, in practice, only certain LBA-48-enabled operating systems, including Linux, FreeBSD and Windows 7 that use 64-bit sector addresses internally actually support this.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Any boot code or operating system using 32-bit sector addresses internally would cause addresses to wrap around accessing this partition and thereby result in serious data corruption over all partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] For disks that present a sector size other than 512 bytes, such as USB external drives, there are limitations as well.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] A sector size of 4096 results in an eight-fold increase in the size of a partition that can be defined using MBR, allowing partitions up to 16 TiB (232 × 4096 bytes) in size.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This may cause unpredictable behaviour as well, and therefore should be avoided when compatibility and standard conformity is an issue.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] On IBM PC-compatible computers, the bootstrapping firmware (contained within the ROM BIOS) loads and executes the master boot record.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The PC/XT (type 5160) used an Intel 8088 microprocessor.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In order to remain compatible, all x86 BIOS architecture systems start with the microprocessor in an operating mode referred to as real mode.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The BIOS reads the MBR from the storage device into physical memory, and then it directs the microprocessor to the start of the boot code.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The BIOS will switch the processor to real mode, then begin to execute the MBR program, and so the beginning of the MBR is expected to contain real-mode machine code.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Since the BIOS bootstrap routine loads and runs exactly one sector from the physical disk, having the partition table in the MBR with the boot code simplifies the design of the MBR program.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] It contains a small program that loads the Volume Boot Record (VBR) of the targeted partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Control is then passed to this code, which is responsible for loading the actual operating system.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Popular MBR code programs were created for booting PC DOS and MS-DOS, and similar boot code remains in wide use.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] These boot sectors expect the `FDISK` partition table scheme to be in use and scans the list of partitions in the MBR's embedded partition table to find the only one that is marked with the *active flag*.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] It then loads and runs the volume boot record (VBR) of the active partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] There are alternative boot code implementations, some of which are installed by boot managers, which operate in a variety of ways.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Some MBR code loads additional code for a boot manager from the first track of the disk, which it assumes to be "free" space that is not allocated to any disk partition, and executes it.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] A MBR program may interact with the user to determine which partition on which drive should boot, and may transfer control to the MBR of a different drive.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Other MBR code contains a list of disk locations (often corresponding to the contents of files in a filesystem) of the remainder of the boot manager code to load and to execute.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] (The first relies on behavior that is not universal across all disk partitioning utilities, most notably those that read and write GPTs.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] On machines that do not use x86 processors, or on x86 machines with non-BIOS firmware such as Open Firmware or Extensible Firmware Interface (EFI) firmware, this design is unsuitable, and the MBR is not used as part of the system bootstrap.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] EFI firmware is instead capable of directly understanding the GPT partitioning scheme and the FAT filesystem format, and loads and runs programs held as files in the EFI System partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR will be involved only insofar as it might contain a partition table for compatibility purposes if the GPT partition table scheme has been used.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] There is some MBR replacement code that emulates EFI firmware's bootstrap, which makes non-EFI machines capable of booting from disks using the GPT partitioning scheme.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] It detects a GPT, places the processor in the correct operating mode, and loads the EFI compatible code from disk to complete this task.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In addition to the bootstrap code and a partition table, master boot records may contain a disk signature.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This is a 32-bit value that is intended to identify uniquely the disk medium (as opposed to the disk unit—the two not necessarily being the same for removable hard disks).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The disk signature was introduced by Windows NT version 3.5, but it is now used by several operating systems, including the Linux kernel version 2.6 and later.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Linux tools can use the NT disk signature to determine which disk the machine booted from.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] It may also be used in Windows NT BOOT.INI files (though most do not), to describe the location of bootable Windows NT (or later) partitions.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The first four bytes are said disk signature.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] (In other keys, these bytes may appear in reverse order from that found in the MBR sector.) These are followed by eight more bytes, forming a 64-bit integer, in little-endian notation, which are used to locate the byte offset of this partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In this case, 00 7E corresponds to the hexadecimal value 0x7E00 (32,256).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] If this disk had another partition with the values 00 F8 93 71 02 following the disk signature (under, e.g., the key value `\DosDevices\D:`), it would begin at byte offset 0x00027193F800 (10,495,457,280), which is also the first byte of physical sector 20,498,940.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Starting with Windows Vista, the disk signature is also stored in the Boot Configuration Data (BCD) store, and the boot process depends on it.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] If the disk signature changes, cannot be found or has a conflict, Windows is unable to boot.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] IBM PC-compatible computers are little-endian, which means the processor stores numeric values spanning two or more bytes in memory least significant byte first.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The format of the MBR on media reflects this convention.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Thus, the MBR signature will appear in a disk editor as the sequence `55 AA`.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The bootstrap sequence in the BIOS will load the first valid MBR that it finds into the computer's physical memory at address 0x7C00 to 0x7DFF.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The last instruction executed in the BIOS code will be a "jump" to that address in order to direct execution to the beginning of the MBR copy.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The primary validation for most BIOSes is the signature at offset 0x01FE, although a BIOS implementer may choose to include other checks, such as verifying that the MBR contains a valid partition table without entries referring to sectors beyond the reported capacity of the disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] To the BIOS, removable (e.g. floppy) and fixed disks are essentially the same.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] For either, the BIOS reads the first physical sector of the media into RAM at absolute address 0x7C00, checks the signature in the last two bytes of the loaded sector, and then, if the correct signature is found, transfers control to the first byte of the sector with a jump (JMP) instruction.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The only real distinction that the BIOS makes is that (by default, or if the boot order is not configurable) it attempts to boot from the first removable disk before trying to boot from the first fixed disk.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] From the perspective of the BIOS, the action of the MBR loading a volume boot record into RAM is exactly the same as the action of a floppy disk volume boot record loading the object code of an operating system loader into RAM.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In either case, the program that the BIOS loaded is going about the work of chain loading an operating system.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The last 66 bytes of the 512-byte MBR are reserved for the partition table and other information, so the MBR boot sector program must be small enough to fit within 446 bytes of memory or less.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR code examines the partition table, selects a suitable partition and loads the program that will perform the next stage of the boot process, usually by making use of INT 13h BIOS calls.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR bootstrap code loads and runs (a boot loader- or operating system-dependent) volume boot record code that is located at the beginning of the "active" partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The volume boot record will fit within a 512-byte sector, but it is safe for the MBR code to load additional sectors to accommodate boot loaders longer than one sector, provided they do not make any assumptions on what the sector size is.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] In fact, at least 1 KB of RAM is available at address 0x7C00 in every IBM XT- and AT-class machine, so a 1 KB sector could be used with no problem.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Like the MBR, a volume boot record normally expects to be loaded at address 0x0000:0x7C00.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] This derives from the fact that the volume boot record design originated on unpartitioned media, where a volume boot record would be directly loaded by the BIOS boot procedure; as mentioned above, the BIOS treats MBRs and volume boot records (VBRs) exactly alike.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Since this is the same location where the MBR is loaded, one of the first tasks of an MBR is to relocate itself somewhere else in memory.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The relocation address is determined by the MBR, but it is most often 0x0000:0x0600 (for MS-DOS/PC DOS, OS/2 and Windows MBR code) or 0x0060:0x0000 (most DR-DOS MBRs).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The *Status* field in a partition table record is used to indicate an active partition.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Standard-conformant MBRs will allow only one partition marked active and use this as part of a sanity-check to determine the existence of a valid partition table.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] They will display an error message, if more than one partition has been marked active.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Some non-standard MBRs will not treat this as an error condition and just use the first marked partition in the row.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Traditionally, values other than 0x00 (not active) and 0x80 (active) were invalid and the bootstrap program would display an error message upon encountering them.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] However, the Plug and Play BIOS Specification and BIOS Boot Specification (BBS) allowed other devices to become bootable as well since 1994.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Consequently, with the introduction of MS-DOS 7.10 (Windows 95B) and higher, the MBR started to treat a set bit 7 as active flag and showed an error message for values 0x01..0x7F only.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] It continued to treat the entry as physical drive unit to be used when loading the corresponding partition's VBR later on, thereby now also accepting other boot drives than 0x80 as valid, however, MS-DOS did not make use of this extension by itself.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Storing the actual physical drive number in the partition table does not normally cause backward compatibility problems, since the value will differ from 0x80 *only* on drives other than the first one (which have not been bootable before, anyway).
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] However, even with systems enabled to boot off other drives, the extension may still not work universally, for example, after the BIOS assignment of physical drives has changed when drives are removed, added or swapped.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] Therefore, per the BIOS Boot Specification (BBS), it is best practice for a modern MBR accepting bit 7 as active flag to pass on the DL value originally provided by the BIOS instead of using the entry in the partition table.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The MBR is loaded at memory location 0x0000:0x7C00 and with the following CPU registers set up when the prior bootstrap loader (normally the IPL in the BIOS) passes execution to it by jumping to 0x0000:0x7C00 in the CPU's real mode.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] While this resolves to the same location in real mode memory, it is non-standard and should be avoided, since MBR code assuming certain register values or not written to be relocatable may not work otherwise.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] DL is supported by IBM BIOSes as well as most other BIOSes.
[src:grub-bootloader/master-boot-record] The Toshiba T1000 BIOS is known not to support this properly, and some old Wyse 286 BIOSes use DL values greater or equal to 2 for fixed disks (thereby reflecting the logical drive numbers under DOS rather than the physical drive numbers of the BIOS).
